        <section id="motion" class="section">
            <h2>Motion</h2>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>average speed(v) = distance travelled(x) / time taken(t)</p>
            <p>v = u+at</p>
            <p> d = 1/2(v+v)t</p>
            <p>s = ut + 1/2at^2</p>
            <p>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</p>
        </section>
        <section id="forces" class="section">
            <h2>Forces In Action</h2>
            <h3>Definitions</h3>
            <p>Principle of Moments: When a body is balanced, the total clockwise moment about a point equals the total
                anticlockwise moment about the same point</p>
            <p>Archimedes' principle: The upthrust exerted on a body immersed in a fluid, whether fully or partially
                submerged, is equal to the weight of the fluid that the body displaces.</p>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>torque = Fd</p>
            <p>moment = Fx</p>
            <p>ρ = m/V</p>
            <p>p = hρg</p>
        </section>
        <section id="energy" class="section">
            <h2>Work, Energy and Power</h2>
            <h3>Definitions</h3>
            <p>Content about work, energy, and power.</p>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>W = Fx cos θ</P>
            <p>efficiency = useful energy output/total energy input × 100%</p>
            <p>P = W/t</p>
            <p>P=Fv</p>
        </section>
        <section id="springs" class="section">
            <h2>Springs and Hooke's Law</h2>
            <p>Hooke's Law: The force is directly proportional to the deformation, as long as the material deos not
                exceed its elastic limit.</p>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>F = kx</p1>
            <p>E = 1/2 x ; E = 1/2 x^2</p1>
            <p> σ = F/A></p1>
            <p>ε = x/L</p1>
            <p>E = σ / ε</p>

        </section>
        <section id="momentum" class="section">
            <h2>Laws of Motion and Momentum</h2>
            <h3>Definitions</h3>
            <p>Content about laws of motion and momentum.</p>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>F = △p/△t</p>
            <p>p = mv</p>
        </section>
        <section id="charge" class="section">
            <h2>Charge and Current</h2>
            <h3>Definitions</h3>
            <p>Kirchhoffs First Law: For any point in an electrical circuit, the sum of currents into that point is
                equal to the sum of currents out of that point.
                I.E. ∑I in = ∑I out
            </p>
            <p>Kirchhoffs Second Law: (From the law of conservation of energy) In any circuit, the sum of the
                electromotive forces is equal to the sum of the p.d.s around a closed loop. I.E. ∑ℰ = ∑V around a closed
                loop.
            </p>
            <p>Electromotive force: Energy transferred from other stores (e.g. Chemical) to electrical energy.</p>
            <p>Potential difference: Energy transferred from electrical energy to other stores (e.g. Thermal)</p>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>∆Q = I∆t</p>
            <p>I = Anev</p>
            <p>W = VQ ; W = ℰQ ; W = VIt</p>

        </section>
        <section id="power" class="section">
            <h2>Energy, Power and Resistance</h2>
            <p>Content about energy, power, and resistance.</p>
            <h3> Equations</h3>
            <p>R = ρL/A</p>
            <p>R = R1 + R2 +…</p>
            <p>1/R = 1/R1 + 1/R2 +...</p>
            <p>P = VI</p>
            <p>P = I^2 R</p>
            <p>P = V^2/R</p>
            <p>ℰ = I(R + r) ; ℰ = V + Ir</p>
            <p> V = IR</p>
            <h3>Forgettable Things</h3>
            <p>The resistance R of a wire is directly proportional to its length L:
                R ∝ L
                This is because doubling the length of the wire doubles the p.d. so the resistance must have doubled
                (V/I = R).
            </p>
            <p>The resistance R of a wire is inversly proportional to tis cross-sectional area A:
                R ∝ 1/L
                This is becouse doubling the A of a wire doubles the current in the wire, therfore resistance must have
                halved (V/I
                = R)
            </p>
        </section>
        <section id="circuits" class="section">
            <h2>Electrical Circuits</h2>
            <p>Content about electrical circuits.</p>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>V(out) = R2 / (R1 + R2) × V(in)</p>
        </section>
        <section id="waves" class="section">
            <h2>Waves</h2>
            <h3>Definitions</h3>
            <p>Principle of Superposition of waves: when two or more waves meet at a point, the resultant displacement
                at that point is equal to the sum of the
                displacements of the individual waves at that point.</p>
            <p>Coherent Waves: Waves with equal or fixed phase difference.</p>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>v = fλ</p>
            <p>f = 1/T</p>
            <p>I = P/A</p>
            <p>λ = ax/D</p>
            <p>n = c/v</p>
            <p>n sinθ = constant</p>
            <p>sin C = 1/n</p>
        </section>
        <section id="quantum" class="section">
            <h2>Quantum Physics</h2>
            <h3>Definitions</h3>
            <p>Content about quantum physics.</p>
            <h3>Equations</h3>
            <p>E = hf ; E = hc/λ</p>
            <p>hf = φ + KE(max)</p>
            <p>λ= h/p</p>
        </section>
        <section id="constants" class="section">
            <h2>Constants</h2>
            <p>acceleration of free fall g 9.81ms^–2</p>
            <p>elementary charge e 1.60 × 10^–19C</p>
            <p>speed of light in a vacuum c 3.00 × 108ms^–1</p>
            <p>Planck constant h 6.63 × 10^–34 Js</p>
            <p>Avogadro constant NA 6.02 × 10^23 mol–1</p>
            <p>molar gas constant R 8.31Jmol–1K–1</p>
            <p>Boltzmann constant k 1.38 × 10^–23 JK–1</p>
            <p>gravitational constant G 6.67 × 10^–11 Nm2 kg–2</p>
            <p>permittivity of free space ε0 8.85 × 10^–12 C2N–1m–2 (Fm–1)</p>
            <p>electron rest mass me 9.11 × 10^–31 kg</p>
            <p>proton rest mass mp 1.673 × 10^–27 kg</p>
            <p>neutron rest mass mn 1.675 × 10^–27 kg</p>
            <p>alpha particle rest mass mα 6.646 × 10^–27 kg</p>
            <p>Stefan constant σ 5.67 × 10^–8cWm–2K–4</p>
        </section>
